      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2005_Solutions_2005s_page_004_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Second solution: (by Calvin Lin) As in the first solution, we may compute the probability that for a particular one of the points 1, the angle at l, is not acute but the following angle is, and then multiply by n. Imagine picking the points by first choosing 1, then picking n - 1 pairs of antipodal points and then picking one member of each pair. Let R2,...,R, be the points of the pairs which lie in the semicircle, taken in order away from 21, and let S2,...,Sn be the antipodes of these. Then to get the desired situation, we must choose from the pairs to end up with all but one of the Si, and we cannot take R, and the other S; or else <Q, will be acute. That gives us (n - 2) good choices out of 2\"-1; since we could have chosen Q, to be any of the n points, the probability is again n(n - 2)2-n+1.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1278195427844694,
          0.8415178569316114,
          0.49060151260400175,
          0.9273313493168618
        ],
